Condition : 46 - Notwithstanding the plans hereby approved, prior to occupation of any part of the development, details of:
-CCTV;
-General external lighting;
-Security lighting;
-Access control measures for residential core entrances;
on or around the buildings or within the site in the development shall be submitted to and approved in writing by
the Local Planning Authority and installed prior to the first occupation of the development. The details shall include the location and full specification of all lighting and include an assessment of the impact of any such lighting on the surrounding residential environment. Prior to occupation of any of the residential units, details of a post installation inspection of external light levels shall be submitted to and approved in writing to demonstrate that the built project meets the projected light level evels. The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details so approved and
shall be maintained as such thereafter.
Reason: To safeguard the security of the development and to ensure that any resulting general or security lighting and CCTV are appropriately located, designed to not adversely impact on neighbouring residential amenity or ecology, and are appropriate to the overall design of the development in accordance with policies 7.3, 7.4, 7.6 and 7.19 of the London Plan and Policy DMS1 and DMO4 of the Wandsworth Local Plan.

Condition : 54 - INFORMATIVE: In regards to condition 44, the applicant is advised that a list of possible air pollution mitigation measures are as follows:
- A list of Opening windows restrictions to avoid exposure to road-traffic pollution
- Altering layout so habitable rooms are sited away from source of poor air quality;
- Non-residential usage of lower floors;
- Altering footprint by siting further away from source of poor air quality.
- Use of passive or active air conditioning;
- Use of acoustic ventilators;
- High thermal insulation and the use of passive solar-heating through building orientation and good design will reduce the use of gas-heating and air-conditioning and reduce emissions of nitrogen oxides (NOx);
- Inlets to ventilation systems located as high as practical above ground level, preferably at roof height. They should not be located where the exhaust from energy plant will affect the quality of the inlet air;
- Use of Mechanical Ventilation Heat Recovery (MVHR) system.
